title: A Safety, Pharmacokinetic, and Pharmacodynamic Study of LY2886721 in Healthy Subjects and Patients Diagnosed With Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief:
This study is being done for the following reasons:

To determine the safety of LY2886721 and any side effects that may be associated with it and to see how much of the study drug is in the blood and the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) when one dose is given to healthy participants and participants diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease. It will also look at how safe and tolerable the study drug is when given to healthy participants in higher doses.

This research study is being conducted in three groups, referred to as Groups (Cohorts) A, B, or C.

Group A will enroll participants with Alzheimer's disease while Groups B and C will enroll healthy participants.

For Group A or B, participation in this research study could last up to 34 days. For Group C, participation could last up to 60 days.

outcomeMeasures.title: Cohort C: Mean QTcF Value at Cmax
outcomeMeasures.description: The mean QTcF value at Cmax for participants administered a single dose of 280 mg LY2886721 was reported. The QT interval is a measure of the time between the start of the Q wave and the end of the T wave and was calculated from electrocardiogram (ECG) data using Fridericia's formula: QTc = QT/RR\^0.33. Corrected QT (QTc) is the QT interval corrected for heart rate and RR, which is the interval between two R waves. Time matched mean change from baseline in QTcF = time matched plasma concentration + participant + random error.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Participants who received at least one dose of LY2886721 at the 280-mg dose level and with evaluable mean QTcF data.
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Predose up to 48 hours after administration of study drug

explanation_target: Reason: The protocol describes LY2886721 given to healthy and Alzheimer's participants to assess safety, pharmacokinetics, CSF penetration and pharmacodynamics (target engagement), which indicates a therapeutic intended to modify disease biology rather than only treat symptoms.

Key fact — drug identity & mechanism: LY2886721 is a small-molecule β‑secretase (BACE1) inhibitor developed by Eli Lilly, designed to lower amyloid-β production (disease-pathology targeting). citeturn0search0turn0search6

Pharmacology / clinical PD: Phase 1 studies showed CSF and plasma Aβ lowering and BACE1 activity reduction consistent with target engagement; LY2886721 was evaluated in healthy volunteers and AD patients in early-phase trials. citeturn0search2turn0search4
Safety note from sponsor: Lilly voluntarily terminated a Phase II study of LY2886721 in 2013 due to abnormal liver biochemical tests observed during monitoring. citeturn0search0

Act (classification): The intervention is a small-molecule protease inhibitor aimed at reducing amyloid production (disease-modifying mechanism), so it matches the 'disease-targeted small molecule' category rather than a biologic, cognitive enhancer, or neuropsychiatric symptom treatment.

Reflect: The trial description (safety, PK/PD, CSF Aβ measurements) and multiple sources confirming BACE1 inhibition support classification as a disease-targeted small molecule. No evidence the compound is a biologic, symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or an intervention for neuropsychiatric symptoms; therefore 'disease-targeted small molecule' is the correct category.
explanation_agent: Reason: The trial drug LY2886721 is a small-molecule β‑secretase (BACE1) inhibitor intended to lower production of amyloid‑β (Aβ) — i.e., it targets the amyloid pathway of AD pathogenesis, which maps directly to CADRO category A (Amyloid beta). citeturn0search2turn0search1

Act: Extracted facts — drug name: LY2886721; mechanism: BACE1 (β‑secretase) inhibition; modality: disease‑targeted small molecule; endpoints described include safety, PK/PD, CSF penetration and CSF Aβ measurements (target engagement). These details justify assigning A) Amyloid beta. citeturn0search6turn0search2

Reflect: The available trial description and multiple sources confirm the compound specifically targets the amyloid production pathway rather than symptomatic neurotransmission, inflammation, etc. Although the program was later halted for safety (abnormal liver tests) this is a safety outcome, not a change in mechanism — so the correct CADRO classification remains A) Amyloid beta (not multi‑target or Other). citeturn0search0turn0search2

Web search results (key sources used): 1) Eli Lilly press release reporting voluntary termination of the Phase II LY2886721 study due to abnormal liver biochemical tests (June 13, 2013). citeturn0search0 2) ALZFORUM therapeutic entry summarizing LY2886721 as a Lilly BACE inhibitor, Phase 1/2 development, CSF Aβ lowering and target engagement. citeturn0search2 3) NCATS / drug summary page noting LY2886721 reached Phase 2, described Phase 1 studies with CSF sampling and robust reductions in CSF Aβ and sAPPβ consistent with BACE1 inhibition. citeturn0search1 4) Neurology abstract reporting PK/PD results (dose‑dependent plasma and CSF Aβ reductions after 14 days). citeturn0search6
